did.unittitle: Fine Art Prints of New York City
did.physloc: Department of Prints, Photographs, and Architectural Collections
did.abstract: Collection of art prints showing views of and scenes in New York City. Includes engravings, etchings, lithographs, and other printmaking processes.

custodhist.head: Provenance
custodhist.p: Acquisition dates span the period of the collection. Specific dates of acquisition can often be found on the verso of each print.

accessrestrict.head: Access Restrictions
accessrestrict.p: Photocopying undertaken by staff only. Limited to twenty exposures of stable, unbound material per day. See guidelines in Print Room for details.

prefercite.head: Preferred Citation
prefercite.p: This collection should be cited as Fine Art Prints of New York City, PR 229, Department of Prints, Photographs, and Architectural Collections, The New-York Historical Society.

scopecontent.head: Scope and Content Note
scopecontent.p: The Fine Art Prints of New York City collection spans the nineteenth and twentieth centuries. It is divided into three series by size: Medium Format Prints, Large Format Prints, and Oversize Prints.

Prints in the collection are mainly focused on the architecture and public life of New York City; points of local interest-including various skylines of Manhattan, the Brooklyn Bridge, Central Park, the New York Stock Exchange, the Woolworth Building, and the World Trade Center-are well-represented. Numerous prints depict religious architecture, including several views of Grace Church of Wall Street, and buildings of historical importance. Views of "old New York" are also common, including homesteads in Brooklyn and small historic views of homesteads and small homes in Manhattan. Only a few prints depict life in Chinatown or the poorer areas of the city. The prints from the first half of the twentieth century, however, are comprehensive in their portrayal of the increasingly modern New York -- images of skyscrapers, bridges, and commercial buildings abound.

The collection is mainly composed of etchings; a small percentage is engravings, lithographs, aquatints, or linoleum cuts. Notations on the format of the prints, and the edition number if known, can be found after the print title.

Important New York artists from throughout the twentieth century are represented in the collection. Artists with four or more prints include: Paul Berdanier, Arthur Cohen, K. Dehman, John Mackie Falconer, Agnes B. Fernbach, Albert Flanagan, Julius F. Gayler, Joseph W. Golinkin, Edward S. Hewitt, F. Leo Hunter, Nat Lowell, William Meyerowitz, Charles F.W. Mielatz, Betty Waldo Parish, Philip Reisman, Shunji Sakuyama, Anton Schutz, T.F. Simon, Emily Trueblood, William H. Wallace, Charles Henry White, Lawrence Nelson Wilbur, and Louis Wolchonok.

In addition, the collection includes small samples of the work of John Taylor Arms, Gottlob Briem, Fritz Eichenberg, Red Grooms, Richard Haas, Childe Hassam, Martin Lewis, James Pennell, Ernest D. Roth, and Richard Sloat.

Women printmakers found here include Isabel Bishop, Edith Bry, Mabel Dwight, Su-Li Hung, Yvonne Jacquette, Wuanita Smith, Caroline Phelps Stokes, and Karen Whitman, in addition to Fernbach, Parish, and Trueblood.

arrangement.head: Arrangement
arrangement.p: The collection is divided into three series by size. Within each series, prints are arranged alphabetically by artist.

relatedmaterial.head: Related Material at the Department of Prints, Photographs, and Architectural Collections
relatedmaterial.p: Similar works by many of the artists found within this collection can also be found in the James Boyd Collection of New York City Etchings (PR 007) and in the Printmaker File (PR 058).

scopecontent.head: Scope and Contents note
scopecontent.p: Series I contains prints size 16 x 20 inches and smaller. Prints are arranged alphabetically by artist's surname and title of print; titles listed are assigned by artist while [descriptions appear in brackets]. All prints are black and white etchings unless otherwise described; dates are given if inscribed by artist or in plate.
